<h4>
    Part 3: Walk-through question
</h4>
<ol class="questionList">
    <li class="question">
        You place a piece of steel with a mass of 0.500 kg into a bowl
        of water with a mass of 2.00 kg.
        The steel has an initial temperature of 30.0 degrees Celsius
        and the water has an initial temperature of 20.0 degrees Celsius.
        Assume no energy is lost form the system.
        Both objects must have the same final temperature (That is the zeroth law of Thermodynamics.
        Our ultimate goal is to determine this final temperature.
        <ol class="subQuestionList" type = 'A'>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer ="Heat flows from the steel to the water.">
                Explain how heat energy flows (from what to what?)
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = "The temperature of the steel decreases.">
                What happens to the temperature of the steel?
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = "The temperature of the water increases.">
                What happens to the temperature of the water?
            </li>
            <h5>
                Explanation:
            </h5>
            <p>
                According to Newton's First Law of Thermodynamics (The Conservation of energy),
                if no energy enters of leaves the system, as is stated above,
                the total energy of the system of the water and steel must remain constant.
                Because the variable \( Q \) represents the energy that enters a particular
                object, we have the formula:
                $$
                Q_w + Q_s = 0
                $$
                In this formula \( Q_w \) is the heat that enters the water
                and \( Q_s \) is the heat that enters the steel.
                Note that, for this formula to be satisfied, one of the variables (\(Q_q \)) must
                be positive and the other ( \( Q_s \) ) must be negative.
            </p>
            <p>

            </p>
            <p>
                The next step is to fill in the equation above with relevant variables,
                based on the formula for Q:
                $$
                Q = m C (T_f - T_i)
                $$
                According to the 0th Law of Thermodynamics, the two substances
                must end with the same final temperature.
                Thus, the final temperature of the water \( T_fw \) and the final
                temperature of the steel \( T_fs \) can be represented by a single
                variable \( T_f \), the final temperature of the mixture.
                $$
                Q_w = m_w C_w ( T_f - T_{iw} )
                \\
                Q_w = m_s C_s ( T_f - T_{is} )
                $$
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    \( m_w = \) mass of the water
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( C_w = \) specific heat of the water
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( T_{iw} = \) initial temperature of the water
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( m_s = \) mass of the steel
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( C_s = \) specific heat of the steel
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( T_{is} = \) initial temperature of the steel
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( T_f = \) final temperature of the mixture
                </li>
            </ul>
            <div class="pageBreak"></div>
            <p>
                Finally, our formula can be combined to create the following common formula:
                $$
                Q_w + Q_s = 0
                \\
                m_w C_w ( T_f - T_{iw} ) + m_s C_s ( T_f - T_{is} ) = 0
                $$
                This is the equation we must solve.
                The variable includes seven variables. Six are known,
                and the one unkown variable is \( T_f \), the final temperature of the mixture.
            </p>
            <p>
                Here is a space for you to write down the values of known variables:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    \( m_w = \)
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( C_w = \)
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( T_{iw} = \)
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( m_s = \)
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( C_s = \)
                </li>
                <li>
                    \( T_{is} = \)
                </li>
            </ul>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( 2 \cdot 4184 \cdot ( T_f - 20) + 0.5 \cdot 470 \cdot (T_f - 30) = 0 \)'>
                Plug in the known above to create an equation for the final temperature \( T_f \)
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '20.27316 degrees Celsius'>
                Solve the equation above to determine the final temperature of the mixture. Write you answer with 7 significant figures of accuracy.
            </li>
            <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '20.3 degrees Celsius'>
                Round your answer for the final temperature of the mixture to 3 significant figures of accuracy.
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
</ol>

